You said:
Are there open source tools that allow you to do things like plot data points on a map? Looking to experiment with school boundary maps without using a proprietary system.
ChatGPT said:

Below are some widely-used open-source options you can mix and match, depending on whether you prefer a desktop GUI, a low-code web app, or full programmatic control.

1. Desktop GIS (all-in-one)

ToolWhat it does wellTypical use in a boundary-mapping workflow
QGIS 3.44Full desktop GIS with symbology, geoprocessing, and plug-ins. Runs on Windows, macOS, Linux, and even Android via QField.• Import shapefiles or GeoJSON of district boundaries.
• Join student address points (CSV/Excel) and display them as symbols sized or colored by grade.
• Draw or edit proposed attendance zones, run area/length measures, export to PDF or GeoPackage.

Why choose it? It is feature-complete yet community-driven, and you own the project files—no license lock-in.

2. Browser-based mapping libraries (JavaScript)

LibraryStrengthsWhen to use
Leaflet.jsLightweight, easy to learn, huge plugin ecosystem.Embedding an interactive boundary map on a website or internal portal. leafletjs.com
MapLibre GL JSSuccessor to Mapbox GL under an open license; renders vector tiles with WebGL for smooth panning/zooming.When you want fast, styleable vector boundaries and “slippy-map” feel without Mapbox fees. maplibre.org
OpenLayers (not searched above, but another mature option)Rich GIS functions (buffer, intersects, etc.) in the browser.Advanced spatial analysis in a pure web stack.

3. Zero-install, drag-and-drop web apps

ToolHighlightsIdeal for
Kepler.glUpload CSV, GeoJSON, or Shapefile right in the browser; auto-detects lat/long, offers heatmaps, choropleths, time sliders; stores data only in your browser.Rapid exploration or board-room demos of boundaries and student clusters without any coding. kepler.gl

4. Python “notebook-friendly” libraries

LibraryKey featuresExample
GeoPandasAdds spatial types and operations to pandas (clip, dissolve, centroid, etc.).Read student CSV → convert to GeoDataFrame → spatial-join with zone polygons to see counts per zone. geopandas.org
FoliumPython wrapper around Leaflet; turn your GeoPandas result into an interactive HTML map with a single line.Share a self-contained HTML of proposed boundaries by email. python-visualization.github.io

Tip: If you prefer R, {sf}, {tmap}, and {leaflet} offer similar power.

5. Server-side components (optional, but powerful at district scale)

ComponentRoleBenefit
PostGISSpatial extension for PostgreSQL.Central “single source of truth” for parcels, student addresses, attendance zones; supports advanced spatial SQL (e.g., find students within 1 mile of a proposed boundary). PostGIS
GeoServerPublishes layers from PostGIS (or files) as WMS/WFS/WMTS services and styles them with SLD.Feed tiled or feature services to Leaflet, MapLibre, QGIS, or any other OGC-compliant client. geoserver.org

Putting it together – a quick “school boundary sandbox”

  1. Gather data

    • Boundary polygons: export current zones from your SIS or download TIGER/Line school district shapefiles.

    • Student geocoded addresses: CSV with latitude, longitude.

  2. Prototype in QGIS or Kepler.gl

    • Drag both layers in, symbolize, and inspect overlaps or outliers.

    • Use QGIS’s Processing ► Polygonize or Split tools to sketch new scenarios.

  3. Stand up a lightweight stack if you need sharing

    text
    PostGIS (data store)  →  GeoServer (OGC & tiles)  →  Leaflet/MapLibre front-end

    You can containerize all three with Docker for a no-install lab environment.

  4. Automate analysis with Python

    • Use GeoPandas to batch-test “what-if” rezoning scenarios and output summary tables.

    • Push results back to PostGIS for live visualization.

Choosing the right starting point

If you want…Start with
GUI, no codingQGIS
Interactive web map with minimal codeLeaflet or Folium
Drag-and-drop visual storytellingKepler.gl
Scalable backend for multiple usersPostGIS + GeoServer

All of the tools above are licensed under GPL, BSD, or MIT-style licenses, so you can deploy them on-premises without any vendor lock-in. As your experiments grow, you can layer these components rather than replace them.

Below are the most common Microsoft- and Google-based workflows that let you drop address points on a map, sketch or import proposed attendance zones, and share the result—without buying additional proprietary GIS licenses.

Microsoft ecosystem

Power BI Desktop / ServiceFour built-in visuals—Map, Filled Map, ArcGIS Map, and Shape Map. Shape Map can load your custom boundary file once it is converted to TopoJSON, making it ideal for proposed zones. All visuals auto-geocode addresses or lat/long. Microsoft Learn

Typical Microsoft workflow for a boundary sandbox

  1. Prepare data in Excel (student address list with columns Address, City, State  — or Latitude, Longitude).

  2. Use Insert ▶ 3D Map to verify geocoding and spot obvious errors.

  3. Export the cleaned point layer to CSV, then pull both the CSV and a TopoJSON of attendance zones into Power BI. Shape Map will shade zones, while the basic Map visual shows individual students; slicers let you toggle grade levels or scenarios.

  4. Publish to Power BI Service and share a secure link with principals or board members.

This entire stack is covered by your Microsoft 365 license except Azure Maps, which is only needed if you want a home-grown web viewer.

Google ecosystem

ToolWhat it lets you doKey limits / notes

Typical Google workflow

  1. Geocode student addresses in a Google Sheet with a free add-on (or external geocoder if you need >2,500/day).

  2. Open Google My Maps, choose Import, and select the Sheet. My Maps places each student and lets you color-code by grade.

  3. Click Add Layer, choose Draw line or shape, and sketch new boundary ideas (or import a KML/GeoJSON file you prepared elsewhere).

  4. Export KMZ for board packets or embed the live map in a Google Site.

Data-privacy reminder

Student addresses are protected information. Whichever platform you choose, geocode through a service that complies with your district’s data-sharing rules (e.g., use Bing Maps under the Microsoft school agreement, or batch-geocode on-premises) and lock map links to internal viewers only.

You said:
with google my maps, once I import the csv file with location data and map the items, is there a way to draw shapes and capture which data (students) fall within that drawn shape?
ChatGPT said:

The short answer

No—Google My Maps doesn’t have a built‑in “point‑in‑polygon” or spatial‑query tool. You can draw a polygon and you can see the dots sitting inside it, but My Maps can’t automatically list or export the student records that fall inside that shape. The platform was designed for light visualisation and explicitly “lacks common geospatial analysis tools, like spatial querying between layers” gi Perspective.

Below are three practical work‑arounds that stay entirely in the Google (or almost‑Google) ecosystem and get you to the same result without buying extra GIS licences.

Option A BigQuery GIS (point‑in‑polygon at spreadsheet scale)

BigQuery’s GEOGRAPHY data type and ST_WITHIN function give you a one‑line SQL solution—ideal if you’re comfortable with Google Cloud projects.

  1. Export what you already have

    • My Maps ► Menu › Export to KML/KMZ to grab the polygon layer (or all layers) as KML ‏Google Help.

    • Use any converter (e.g., mapshaper.org) to turn the polygon KML into GeoJSON or WKT.

  2. Load data into BigQuery

    • Upload the student CSV; in the schema, create a GEOGRAPHY column with

      sql
      ST_GEOGPOINT(longitude, latitude)

    • Upload the polygon GeoJSON the same way (one row = one zone).

  3. Run the spatial query

    sql
    SELECT s.*, z.zone_name
FROM `fps.students`  AS s
JOIN `fps.boundaries` AS z
ON   ST_WITHIN(s.geom, z.geom);   -- “point in polygon”

    The same SQL pattern is used in Google’s own lightning‑strike demo (see the ST_WITHIN example) Google Cloud.

  4. Export the result as CSV, bring it back into Sheets or re‑import to a new My Maps layer for styling.

Why choose this route? It’s serverless, handles tens of thousands of points instantly, and is already free up to the first 1 TB of query traffic each month.

Option B Google Earth Engine (no‑cost, browser notebook)

If you prefer a point‑and‑click code notebook without setting up Cloud billing:

javascript
// 1. Load the two datasets you exported from My Maps
var students  = ee.FeatureCollection('users/you/students_csv');
var boundary  = ee.FeatureCollection('users/you/attendance_zone');

// 2. Filter points that fall inside the polygon
var inside = students.filterBounds(boundary);

// 3. Export to Drive
Export.table.toDrive({
  collection: inside,
  description: 'students_in_zone',
  fileFormat: 'CSV'
});

Earth Engine runs entirely in the browser and the export lands in your Google Drive, ready for My Maps or Sheets. It’s perfect for quick experiments and supports far larger datasets than My Maps will accept.

Option C DIY web map with Apps Script + Maps JavaScript API

When you need an interactive “draw a shape, get the list” tool but want to stay 100 % in Google Workspace:

  1. Create a new Google Site or HTML file in Apps Script.

  2. Load the Maps JS API (free inside Google Workspace quotas).

  3. Add the Geometry Library and use google.maps.geometry.poly.containsLocation() to test each marker after the user draws a polygon.

  4. Write the IDs of the matching markers back to a Sheet or pop them in a modal.

This takes ~50 lines of code and avoids Cloud billing, but it is a mini‑development project.

Quick comparison

GoalBest route
One‑off list for board packetBigQuery GIS
Repeatable analysis, larger than My Maps limitsEarth Engine
Interactive “draw and filter” app for principalsApps Script + Maps API
No coding at allPre‑compute the zone column in QGIS, then import to My Maps

Tips specific to school data

  • Protect student privacy. Geocode on‑prem or via Bing Maps (covered by Microsoft A3/A5 licences) if you’re concerned about sending addresses to external geocoders.

  • Keep one authoritative zone file. Whether you store it in BigQuery or Drive, version‑control the polygon so every scenario you run uses the same geometry.

  • Automate the refresh. A scheduled BigQuery query or Earth Engine task can drop a daily CSV in Drive, so your My Maps boundary layer is always current.

What if I want option c, but I don’t care if it is a google tool.
ChatGPT said:

Below is a proven way to build a “draw a shape, return the points inside” sandbox without relying on Google. Everything runs in a single HTML page that you can host on any web server (or open from your desktop) and can later be expanded into a full-blown web app.

1. Choose your client-side stack

StackWhen to choose itEssential pieces
Leaflet + Leaflet.draw + Turf.jsSimple, lightweight, works in every browser, good up to roughly 5–10 k points before you notice lag.Leaflet map core, Leaflet.draw for the polygon tool leaflet.github.io, Turf.js booleanPointInPolygon for the spatial test turfjs.org
MapLibre GL JS + mapbox-gl-draw + Turf.jsYou expect tens of thousands of points, want smooth WebGL rendering, and prefer vector-tile styling.MapLibre GL JS, the open-source fork of Mapbox GL; draw plug-in listed on MapLibre’s own plug-in page MapLibre, NPM package @telida/maplibre-gl-draw or similar npm
OpenLayers + ol-interaction-Draw + Turf.jsYou need more GIS-like functions (buffer, intersects) in pure JS.OpenLayers map core, its built-in draw interaction, plus Turf.js

For a first experiment Leaflet wins on simplicity, so the walk-through below uses it.

2. Prepare your student data

  1. Start with a CSV that contains at least lat and lon columns (and any identifiers you want to retrieve later).

  2. Convert the CSV to GeoJSON if you wish, but you can also read it directly in the browser with Papa Parse.

csv
student_id,grade,lat,lon
S123,4,46.8751,-96.7807
S124,3,46.9122,-96.7894
...

3. Build the page (minimal example)

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <title>Boundary Sandbox</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://unpkg.com/leaflet@1.9.4/dist/leaflet.css" />
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://unpkg.com/leaflet-draw@1.0.4/dist/leaflet.draw.css" />
  <style>#map { height: 95vh; }</style>
</head>
<body>
<div id="map"></div>

<script src="https://unpkg.com/leaflet@1.9.4/dist/leaflet.js"></script>
<script src="https://unpkg.com/leaflet-draw@1.0.4/dist/leaflet.draw.js"></script>
<script src="https://unpkg.com/@turf/turf@6.5.0/turf.min.js"></script>
<script src="https://unpkg.com/papaparse@5.4.3/papaparse.min.js"></script>

<script>
// 1. Map setup
const map = L.map('map').setView([46.8772, -96.7898], 11);
L.tileLayer('https://{s}.tile.openstreetmap.org/{z}/{x}/{y}.png', {
  attribution: '&copy; OSM contributors'
}).addTo(map);

// 2. Load student points from CSV
let studentFeatures = [];
Papa.parse('students.csv', {
  download: true,
  header: true,
  complete: (results) => {
    studentFeatures = results.data.map(row => {
      const marker = L.circleMarker([row.lat, row.lon], { radius: 4 }).addTo(map);
      marker.feature = row; // stash the full record
      return marker;
    });
  }
});

// 3. Enable the draw tool
const drawControl = new L.Control.Draw({
  draw: { polygon: true, polyline: false, marker: false, circle: false, rectangle: false }
});
map.addControl(drawControl);

// 4. Handle completed drawings
map.on(L.Draw.Event.CREATED, (e) => {
  const polygon = e.layer;           // Leaflet polygon layer
  map.addLayer(polygon);

  // Convert to GeoJSON for Turf
  const polyJSON = polygon.toGeoJSON();

  // Test each student
  const inside = studentFeatures.filter(pt => {
    const pJSON = turf.point(pt.getLatLng().toArray());
    return turf.booleanPointInPolygon(pJSON, polyJSON); // true if inside
  });

  // 5. Show the list
  const ids = inside.map(pt => pt.feature.student_id);
  alert('Students in zone: ' + ids.join(', '));

  // (Optional) send ids to a server-side API or trigger a CSV download
});
</script>
</body>
</html>

How it works

  • Leaflet.draw fires the CREATED event when the user finishes a polygon.

  • Each marker’s coordinate is wrapped in a Turf point, then Turf’s booleanPointInPolygon returns true or false.

  • You can replace the alert() with a sidebar table, an API POST, or a client-side CSV download.

4. Scaling up or styling better

  • More points. Switch to MapLibre GL JS. The draw plug-in API is nearly identical, and Turf works with the same GeoJSON objects.

  • Persist shapes. Save each drawn polygon to a database (for example PostGIS) through a simple fetch POST, then reload as GeoJSON so multiple users see each other’s scenarios.

  • Export. Use FileSaver.js or SheetJS to push the inside array straight to Excel.

5. Server-side enhancement (optional)

If you later move the point-in-polygon test to the server:

  1. Store the student table and boundary table in PostGIS.

  2. Expose an API endpoint /students-in-zone that receives polygon GeoJSON and runs

    sql
    SELECT * FROM students
WHERE ST_Within(geom, ST_GeomFromGeoJSON($1)::geometry);

  3. Return JSON or CSV. The front-end code above changes from Turf to a fetch() call.

This reduces browser CPU use and means a principal can upload a 100 k-student file without crashes.

6. Next steps for Fargo Public Schools

  1. Pick the library (Leaflet if you want fast prototyping, MapLibre if you anticipate very large datasets).

  2. Set up a Git repository and drop the starter HTML in it.

  3. Add your real CSV and verify that draw-and-filter works.

  4. Decide whether you need server persistence and, if so, stand up a tiny Node or Python backend and a PostGIS container.

Let me know which piece you would like fleshed out first—data conversion, the styling panel, or a server endpoint—and I can provide the focused code and configuration details.

  1. Uncaught SyntaxError: Invalid or unexpected token (line 55)
    Something in your index.html JavaScript is malformed (often from copy/paste, a hidden BOM character, or smart quotes).

  2. Papa is not defined
    PapaParse never loaded (no script tag pointing to a valid file), so the CSV parser/exporter isn’t available.

  3. favicon.ico 404
    Harmless, you can ignore it.

Fix in 5–10 minutes

A. Add PapaParse locally (no CDN)

  1. Download papaparse.min.js (right‑click “Save link as…”):
    https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mholt/PapaParse/master/papaparse.min.js

  2. In your repo, create a folder: /vendor
    Upload papaparse.min.js into it.

  3. In index.html, before your main app script block, insert:

html
<script src="vendor/papaparse.min.js"></script>

Delete any previous PapaParse <script> tags and any document.write fallback you added.

B. Fix the syntax error

  1. In DevTools, click the line number in the error (55). It will open the file at the offending line.

  2. Look for:

    • Curly “smart” quotes instead of ' or ".

    • A stray character at the file start (often �).

    • Incomplete string/template literal (missing closing ) or `).

  3. Replace the bad line, or just replace the entire JS block with a known-good copy.

Quickest path: Replace everything from <script> (where the app code starts) down to </script> with this working block:

html
<script>
/* === config === */
const DEFAULT_SUMMARY_CATEGORICAL = ['grade','school','PROGRAM','ELL','IEP'];
const DEFAULT_RATE_LIMIT_MS = 1100;
const CENTER = [46.8772, -96.7898];

/* === globals === */
let studentMarkers = [];
let studentRows = [];
let lastSelectionRows = [];
let drawnItemsGroup = L.featureGroup();

/* === map === */
const map = L.map('map').setView(CENTER, 11);
L.tileLayer('https://{s}.tile.openstreetmap.org/{z}/{x}/{y}.png', {
  attribution:'&copy; OpenStreetMap contributors'
}).addTo(map);
drawnItemsGroup.addTo(map);

const drawControl = new L.Control.Draw({
  draw:{ polygon:true, rectangle:true, marker:false, circle:false, polyline:false, circlemarker:false },
  edit:{ featureGroup: drawnItemsGroup, edit:true, remove:true }
});
map.addControl(drawControl);

map.on(L.Draw.Event.CREATED, e => { drawnItemsGroup.addLayer(e.layer); recalcSelection(); });
map.on(L.Draw.Event.EDITED, recalcSelection);
map.on(L.Draw.Event.DELETED, recalcSelection);

/* === csv load === */
document.getElementById('csvFile').addEventListener('change', e => {
  const file = e.target.files[0]; if(!file) return;
  Papa.parse(file, {
    header:true, dynamicTyping:false, skipEmptyLines:true,
    complete: async res => {
      clearMap();
      studentRows = res.data;
      if(!studentRows.length){ alert('CSV appears empty'); return; }
      const cols = Object.keys(studentRows[0]);
      const latKey = cols.find(c => /^(lat|latitude|y)$/i.test(c.trim()));
      const lonKey = cols.find(c => /^(lon|lng|longitude|x)$/i.test(c.trim()));
      if(latKey && lonKey){
        addMarkersFromLatLon(studentRows, latKey, lonKey);
        fitToMarkers();
        alert('Loaded '+studentMarkers.length+' points. Draw a polygon to select.');
      }else{
        const u = cols.map(c=>c.toUpperCase());
        if(!['ADDRESS','CITY','STATE','ZIP'].every(c=>u.includes(c))){
          alert('CSV must have LAT/LON (or X/Y) or ADDRESS,CITY,STATE,ZIP.');
          return;
        }
        await geocodeAndAddMarkers(
          studentRows,
          cols[u.indexOf('ADDRESS')],
          cols[u.indexOf('CITY')],
          cols[u.indexOf('STATE')],
          cols[u.indexOf('ZIP')]
        );
        fitToMarkers();
        alert('Loaded '+studentMarkers.length+' geocoded points. Draw a polygon to select.');
      }
    }
  });
});

function clearMap(){
  studentMarkers.forEach(m => map.removeLayer(m));
  studentMarkers = [];
  studentRows = [];
  lastSelectionRows = [];
  drawnItemsGroup.clearLayers();
  document.getElementById('info').style.display='none';
  document.getElementById('downloadSelected').disabled = true;
}

function addMarkersFromLatLon(rows, latKey, lonKey){
  rows.forEach(r => {
    const lat = parseFloat(r[latKey]), lon = parseFloat(r[lonKey]);
    if(isFinite(lat) && isFinite(lon) && lat!==0 && lon!==0){
      const marker = L.circleMarker([lat, lon], {radius:4});
      marker.feature = r;
      marker.addTo(map);
      studentMarkers.push(marker);
    }
  });
}

function fitToMarkers(){
  if(studentMarkers.length){
    map.fitBounds(L.featureGroup(studentMarkers).getBounds().pad(0.1));
  }
}

async function geocodeAndAddMarkers(rows, addrK, cityK, stateK, zipK){
  const prog = document.getElementById('progress');
  prog.style.display='block';
  for(let i=0;i<rows.length;i++){
    prog.textContent = `Geocoding ${i+1} / ${rows.length}`;
    const r = rows[i];
    const addr = [r[addrK], r[cityK], r[stateK], r[zipK]].filter(Boolean).join(', ');
    try{
      const loc = await geocodeAddress(addr);
      if(loc){
        const marker = L.circleMarker([loc.lat, loc.lon], {radius:4});
        marker.feature = r;
        marker.addTo(map);
        studentMarkers.push(marker);
      }else{ r.__geocode_failed = true; }
    }catch(err){ r.__geocode_failed = true; }
    await sleep(DEFAULT_RATE_LIMIT_MS);
  }
  prog.style.display='none';
}

async function geocodeAddress(q){
  const url = 'https://nominatim.openstreetmap.org/search?format=json&limit=1&q=' + encodeURIComponent(q);
  const resp = await fetch(url, { headers:{'Accept-Language':'en'} });
  if(!resp.ok) return null;
  const json = await resp.json();
  if(!json.length) return null;
  return { lat: parseFloat(json[0].lat), lon: parseFloat(json[0].lon) };
}
function sleep(ms){ return new Promise(r=>setTimeout(r, ms)); }

/* === selection & summary === */
function recalcSelection(){
  lastSelectionRows = [];
  if(!drawnItemsGroup.getLayers().length){
    document.getElementById('info').style.display='none';
    document.getElementById('downloadSelected').disabled = true;
    return;
  }
  const polys = drawnItemsGroup.getLayers().map(l=>l.toGeoJSON());
  let unionPoly = null;
  polys.forEach(p=> unionPoly = unionPoly ? turf.union(unionPoly, p) : p);
  if(!unionPoly) return;

  studentMarkers.forEach(m => {
    const p = turf.point([m.getLatLng().lng, m.getLatLng().lat]);
    if(turf.booleanPointInPolygon(p, unionPoly)) lastSelectionRows.push(m.feature);
  });
  renderSelection();
}

function renderSelection(){
  const info = document.getElementById('info');
  const countsDiv = document.getElementById('counts');
  const tableDiv  = document.getElementById('tableContainer');
  const summaryDiv= document.getElementById('summary');
  info.style.display='block';

  countsDiv.innerHTML = '<div class="section-title">Total selected: '+ lastSelectionRows.length +'</div>';

  if(!lastSelectionRows.length){
    tableDiv.innerHTML = '<p>No points inside shapes.</p>';
    summaryDiv.innerHTML = '';
    document.getElementById('downloadSelected').disabled = true;
    return;
  }

  const headers = Object.keys(lastSelectionRows[0]);
  let html = '<table><thead><tr>';
  headers.forEach(h => html += '<th>'+h+'</th>');
  html += '</tr></thead><tbody>';
  lastSelectionRows.forEach(r => {
    html += '<tr>';
    headers.forEach(h => html += '<td>'+ (r[h] ?? '') +'</td>');
    html += '</tr>';
  });
  html += '</tbody></table>';
  tableDiv.innerHTML = html;

  const cfg = deriveSummaryConfig(lastSelectionRows, headers);
  summaryDiv.innerHTML = buildSummaryHTML(lastSelectionRows, cfg);

  document.getElementById('downloadSelected').disabled = false;
}

function deriveSummaryConfig(rows, headers){
  const categorical = [];
  DEFAULT_SUMMARY_CATEGORICAL.forEach(c => {
    const found = headers.find(h => h.toLowerCase() === c.toLowerCase());
    if(found) categorical.push(found);
  });
  if(!categorical.length){
    headers.forEach(h => {
      if(h.startsWith('__')) return;
      const vals = rows.map(r=>r[h]).filter(v=>v!=='' && v!==undefined);
      if(!vals.length) return;
      const numeric = vals.every(v=>!isNaN(parseFloat(v)));
      const uniq = new Set(vals);
      if(!numeric && uniq.size>1 && uniq.size<=15) categorical.push(h);
    });
  }
  const numeric = headers.filter(h=>{
    const vals = rows.map(r=>r[h]).filter(v=>v!=='' && v!==undefined);
    if(!vals.length) return false;
    return vals.every(v=>!isNaN(parseFloat(v)));
  });
  return { categorical, numeric };
}

function buildSummaryHTML(rows, cfg){
  let html = '<div class="section-title">Summary</div>';
  cfg.categorical.forEach(col => {
    const freq = {};
    rows.forEach(r => { const v = r[col] ?? ''; freq[v] = (freq[v]||0)+1; });
    html += '<div><strong>'+col+'</strong><ul>';
    Object.keys(freq).sort().forEach(k => html += '<li>'+k+': '+freq[k]+'</li>');
    html += '</ul></div>';
  });
  cfg.numeric.forEach(col => {
    const vals = rows.map(r=>parseFloat(r[col])).filter(v=>!isNaN(v)).sort((a,b)=>a-b);
    if(!vals.length) return;
    const sum=vals.reduce((a,b)=>a+b,0);
    const mean=sum/vals.length;
    const median= vals.length%2===0 ? (vals[vals.length/2-1]+vals[vals.length/2])/2 : vals[Math.floor(vals.length/2)];
    html += '<div><strong>'+col+'</strong><ul>'+
            '<li>count: '+vals.length+'</li>'+
            '<li>mean: '+round(mean)+'</li>'+
            '<li>median: '+round(median)+'</li>'+
            '<li>min: '+round(vals[0])+'</li>'+
            '<li>max: '+round(vals[vals.length-1])+'</li>'+
            '</ul></div>';
  });
  return html;
}
function round(v){ return Math.round(v*100)/100; }

/* === export === */
document.getElementById('downloadSelected').addEventListener('click', () => {
  if(!lastSelectionRows.length) return;
  const csv = Papa.unparse(lastSelectionRows);
  const blob = new Blob([csv], {type:'text/csv;charset=utf-8;'});
  const url = URL.createObjectURL(blob);
  const a = document.createElement('a');
  a.href=url;
  a.download='selection_'+new Date().toISOString().slice(0,19).replace(/[:T]/g,'-')+'.csv';
  a.click();
  URL.revokeObjectURL(url);
});

/* === summary toggle === */
document.getElementById('toggleSummary').addEventListener('click', () => {
  const s=document.getElementById('summary');
  if(s.style.display==='none'){ s.style.display='block'; this.textContent='Hide Summary'; }
  else { s.style.display='none'; this.textContent='Show Summary'; }
});
</script>
